Shell script block (run: |)
1. echo ...
prints message to workflow console:
Running all classes that expose main() in target/classes.
2. set +e
disable “exit on error” behavior.
after this, a command failing returns non-zero but script continues.
important because some java class executions may fail; we want to attempt all, not abort on first failing program.
3. for file in $(find target/classes -name '*.class' | sort); do
find target/classes -name '*.class': list all .class files below target/classes.
| sort: make deterministic order.
for file in ...: iterate each class file path.
4. cls=${file#target/classes/}
remove prefix target/classes/ from the path.
example: target/classes/com/example/Main.class → com/example/Main.class.
5. cls=${cls%.class}
strip .class suffix from filename.
now com/example/Main.
6. cls=${cls//\//.}
replace / with . (filesystem path -> Java package name).
final example: com.example.Main.
7. if javap -classpath target/classes "$cls" 2>/dev/null | grep -q "public static void main"; then
javap -classpath target/classes "$cls" decompiles class signature (public API only) from compiled class.
2>/dev/null hides stderr warnings from missing classes etc.
grep -q "public static void main" checks if output contains main method declaration.
condition true when this class declares a public static void main(...).
this avoids executing non-entrypoint classes.
8. echo "--- RUNNING: $cls ---"
logs which class is about to run, helpful in Actions output to identify progress/results.
9. java -cp target/classes "$cls"
actually launches Java for this class.
-cp target/classes: uses compiled classpath.
"$cls" is class name (FQCN).
if class has no main, the earlier if guards against calling it.
10. fi
end of if block.
11. done
end of for loop after all class files are processed.
12. set -e
re-enable the default “exit on first error” behavior for following steps.
safe end-of-step to restore normal failure semantics for next steps (Run tests, etc).
Behavior summary
iterates all built classes
filters only main entrypoints with javap + grep
runs each entrypoint one by one
continues through failures (set +e)
returns to strict mode afterwards (set -e)
typed for GitHub Action logs and traceability: list + run + reporting
Important nuance
It may run multiple mains and produce mixed outputs; good for demo code collection but not test-suite style.
If run class requires args, they currently run with no args.
If you want stop on first failure, remove set +e / set -e, or handle statuses explicitly.
